{"id":"2210.12325","submitter":"William Y. C. Chen","authors":"William Y.C. Chen and Amy M. Fu","title":"A Grammatical Calculus for Peaks and Runs of Permutations","comments":"Revised version, 25 pages, 15 figures, to appear in J. Algebraic\n  Combin","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We develop a nonstandard approach to exploring polynomials associated with\npeaks and runs of permutations. With the aid of a context-free grammar, or a\nset of substitution rules, one can perform a symbolic calculus, and the\ncomputation often becomes rather simple. From a grammar it follows at once a\nsystem of ordinary differential equations for the generating functions.\nUtilizing a certain constant property, it is even possible to deduce a single\nequation for each generating function. To bring the grammar to a combinatorial\nsetting, we find a labeling scheme for up-down runs of a permutation, which can\nbe regarded as a refined\n  property, or the differentiability in a certain sense, in contrast to the\nusual counting argument for the recurrence relation. The labeling scheme also\nexhibits how the substitution rules arise in the construction of the\ncombinatorial structures. Consequently,\n  polynomials on peaks and runs can be dealt with in two ways, combinatorially\nor grammatically. The grammar also serves as a guideline to build a bijection\nbetween permutations and increasing trees that maps the number of up-down runs\nto the number of nonroot vertices of even degree. This correspondence can be\nadapted to left peaks and exterior peaks, and the key step of the construction\nis called the reflection principle.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 22 Oct 2022 01:46:20 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 1 Feb 2023 12:58:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-02"}
