{"id":"2211.05577","submitter":"Julia Maddox","authors":"Julia Maddox","title":"Alternate Definitions of Vector Space Dimension and Module Rank Using\n  Isomorphisms","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.RA","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/","abstract":"  The standard definition of the dimension of a vector space or rank of a\nmodule states that dimension or rank is equal to the cardinality of any basis,\nwhich requires an understanding of the concepts of basis, generating set, and\nlinear independence. We pose new definitions for the dimension of a vector\nspace, called the isomorphic dimension, and for the rank of a module, called\nthe isomorphic rank, using isomorphisms. In the finite case, for a vector space\n$V$ over field $F$, its isomorphic dimension is equal $n$ if and only if there\nexists a linear isomorphism from $F^n$ to $V$. For a module $M$ over the\ncommutative ring $R$ with identity, its isomorphic rank is equal to $n$ if and\nonly if there exists an $R$-module isomorphism from $R^n$ to $M$. There are\nsimilar definitions in the infinite cases. These isomorphic definitions do not\nrequire the concepts of basis, generating set, and linear independence. This\napproach allows for some fundamental linear algebra and module theory results\nto be seen more easily or to be proven more similarly to other algebraic proofs\ninvolving isomorphisms and homomorphisms and provides an alternate educational\napproach to dimension and rank.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 22 Oct 2022 08:24:33 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 28 Jan 2023 22:59:49 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 2 Mar 2023 13:03:47 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Fri, 19 May 2023 12:03:39 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-22"}
{"id":"2211.07354","submitter":"Shane Koscielniak Dr","authors":"Shane Rupert Koscielniak","title":"Iterative Learning Control -- Deep Dive","comments":"Poster presented at LLRF Workshop 2022 (LLRF2022, arXiv:2208.13680)","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":"LLRF2022/100","categories":"eess.SY cs.SY","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/","abstract":"  The stability and convergence of an Iterative Learning Controller (ILC) may\nbe assessed either by directly iterating the equations for a variety of inputs,\nor by finding the eigenvalues of the iterated system, or by forming the\nZ-transform and applying pole-zero or equivalent root locus. Two often-used\ncriteria are (i) Asymptotic Convergence (AC) of the difference vectors, and\n(ii) mono-tonic convergence (MC) of the vector norm. The latter (MC) has a Z-\ndomain counterpart. In this paper we apply all three methods and both\nconvergence tests to a simple plant with an ILC wrapper. One, two and\nthree-term learning functions are used. We can then ask the questions: do all\nthe tests work, and do they agree on the stability?\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 21 Oct 2022 17:26:15 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 18 Nov 2022 19:07:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-22"}
